  <div class="marketing" id="about" >
    <div class="container">
    <h1>Introducing microapp.io </h1>
    <div class="row-fluid" style="text-align: justify;margin-top: 40px; ">
      <div class="span12">
        <!--
        <p>You friends might be interested to participate in tiny scientific experiments or challenge requiring small amount of your time, or generate creative fantastic stories requesting  only 1 sentence to each user. See the <a href ="#demo">demo section</a></p>
         MicroApp is a kind of search engine indexing a first fusion table
  representing the stream of your micro-tasks to process, manages the allocation
  of tasks (with a given redundancy) according to your users and send the
  results to another fusion table (output) -->


        <img src="https://docs.google.com/drawings/pub?id=1tK4GCgnKeRYK1JG-0vl6JtjiHsvL49F5l5H9id2tTxg&amp;w=350&amp;h=170"
             style="float:left;margin:10px">
        <p>
          We live in a period of <a href="http://lindastone.net/qa/continuous-partial-attention/" target="_blank">(continous) partial attention</a>: web users contributions follow generally a long tail: few core people and a large majority of volatile users contributing few times.
        </p>
        <p>
          The goal of microapp.io is to tap into the latter segment assuming that the sum of these micro-contributions could leverage a subtantial work (but different from what core contributors will produce).

          Micro-contributions are thus contributions of any kind that someone could quickly make within a small amount of time. <!-- Any of your 200 Facebook friends have no time to peer-review  your 10-page dissertation. However they should be ok to review a tiny portion of it. -->
        </p>

        <p>
           Microapp.io is an *experimental* toolkit to build basic multi-solvers apps broadcasting mini-challenges and gathering micro-contributions from an (open) network of web/mobile users. Up to you to request diverse &amp fun contributions or repetitive &amp; boring ones.<!--It's based on a distributed architecture reusing Google Fusion table as data manager, github as code manager and this tiny server as challenges indexer and contributors manager recommending challenges to contributors. Furthermore transparency (open app = open data + open code) and the easiness of 'clonability' (one button to clone a full app and modify it) facilitate the emergence of an eco-system of apps and best practices. -->


        </p>
        <!-- <p><b>What kind of micro-contributions?</b><br />
     e.g. analyzing a large flow of individual tweets, classifying a large volume of
     images, analyzing a large area on a map, segmenting very quickly a long video
     collaboratively, generating stories via the writing of individual sentences , or
         any kind of big data processable/generable more easily by volatile participants
         than the machine.</p> -->
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
